{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478165"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16996"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16996"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.19,0.04,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9686"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53635"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"4250"},{"type":"tags","id":"8356"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of progressive right eye swelling and fever. He has had a runny nose and cough for the past week. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 105/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There is marked right periorbital swelling with proptosis. His right eye movements are restricted in all directions and painful. There is conjunctival injection and chemosis. His pupils are equal and reactive to light. Visual acuity is reduced in the right eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely predisposing cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute sinusitis","Conjunctivitis","Insect bite","Dental abscess","Local trauma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of orbital cellulitis, characterised by fever, proptosis, restricted eye movements, and reduced visual acuity. These features distinguish it from the more benign preseptal cellulitis. The presence of preceding upper respiratory symptoms is an important clue to the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute sinusitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common predisposing cause of orbital cellulitis in children, particularly affecting the ethmoid sinuses. Infection can spread directly through the thin bony walls of the sinuses or via the valveless veins that connect the sinuses to the orbit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDental abscess\u003C/strong\u003E can occasionally lead to orbital cellulitis, but this is much less common than sinusitis and typically presents with concurrent dental symptoms, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsect bite\u003C/strong\u003E more commonly causes preseptal cellulitis rather than orbital cellulitis. The history would typically include a clear history of a bite, and the infection would typically start superficially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E alone rarely leads to orbital cellulitis. While it can cause eye redness and discharge, it does not typically cause the deep infection characteristic of orbital cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocal trauma\u003C/strong\u003E can predispose to orbital infection but is a less common cause than sinusitis. There would typically be a history of injury, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOrbital cellulitis is a medical emergency requiring urgent CT imaging to confirm the diagnosis and exclude complications such as subperiosteal abscess. Treatment involves broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics to cover common organisms including \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, and anaerobes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute sinusitis is the most common predisposing cause of orbital cellulitis in children.","Orbital cellulitis requires urgent imaging and intravenous antibiotics to prevent vision loss.","Proptosis, reduced eye movements, and conjunctival chemosis are key signs differentiating orbital from preseptal cellulitis."],"references":["Wong SJ, Levi J. Management of pediatric orbital cellulitis: A systematic review. J Pediatr Surg. 2018 Jun;53(6):1206-1212. doi: 10.1016/j.jpedsurg.2018.01.035."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53635"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16996"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53635"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:24:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:25:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9686"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"descripti